5":"1215","1235":"1235","1224":"1224","1201":"1201","1222":"1222","1189":"1189","1200":"1200","Flimby, Cumberland, England, United Kingdom":"Flimby, Cumbraland, England, United Kingdom","harington, cumberland, england ":"Cumbraland, England, United Kingdom","Aldingham, Lancaster, England":"Aldingham, Lancashire, England","Bratton Fleming, Devon, England":"Bratton Fleming, Devon, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1191–1241":"1191–1241","1200–1261":"1200–1261","1201–Male":"1201–Overleden","1215–Male":"1215–Overleden","1180–Female":"1180–Overleden","1222–1297":"1222–1297","1189–1235":"1189–1235","1186–Female":"1186–Overleden","1297":"1297","1241":"1241","1186":"1186","1261":"1261","1191":"1191","1180":"1180","1215":"1215","1235":"1235","1224":"1224","1201":"1201","1222":"1222","1189":"1189","1200":"1200","Flimby, Cumberland, England, United Kingdom":"Flimby, Cumberland, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","harington, cumberland, england ":"Cumberland, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Aldingham, Lancaster, England":"Aldingham, Lancashire, England","Bratton Fleming, Devon, England":"Bratton Fleming, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1191–1241":"1191–1241","1200–1261":"1200–1261","1201–Male":"1201–Deceased","1215–Male":"1215–Deceased","1180–Female":"1180–Deceased","1222–1297":"1222–1297","1189–1235":"1189–1235","1186–Female":"1186–Deceased","1297":"1297","1241":"1241","1186":"1186","1261":"1261","1191":"1191","1180":"1180","1215":"1215","1235":"1235","1224":"1224","1201":"1201","1222":"1222","1189":"1189","1200":"1200","Flimby, Cumberland, England, United Kingdom":"Flimby, Cumberland, England, United Kingdom","harington, cumberland, england ":"Cumberland, England, United Kingdom","Aldingham, Lancaster, England":"Aldingham, Lancashire, England","Bratton Fleming, Devon, England":"Bratton Fleming, Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Harrington","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the three places called Harrington (Cumberland, Lincolnshire, Northamptonshire). The Cumberland placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Hæfer</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The Lincolnshire placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Hearra</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>tūn</i>. The Northamptonshire derives from an Old English personal name <i>Hǣthhere</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Compare   Herendeen  .","Irish: adopted as an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hArrachtáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Arrachtán</i>’, a personal name from a diminutive of <i>arrachtach</i> ‘mighty, powerful’.","Irish: in Kerry, this name was adopted as an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hIongardail</b>, later <b>Ó hUrdáil</b>, ‘descendant of <i>Iongardal</i>’, a personal name of uncertain origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Herington","meanings":["English: variant of   Harrington   or   Herrington  ."]},{"name":"Herrington","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Heronden in Tenterden (Kent) or Herrington in Houghton (Durham). The Kent placename may derive from an Old English personal name <i>Hȳra</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>denn</i> ‘pasture’, while the Durham placename may come from Old English <i>hæring</i> ‘rocky place’ (from <i>hær</i> ‘rock, heap of stones’ + the placename forming suffix <i>-ing</i>) or <i>hæren</i> ‘rocky’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’.","variant of   Harrington  ."]},{"name":"Herendeen","meanings":["Altered form of English   Harrington  ."]},{"name":"Arrington","meanings":["English:","variant of   Harrington   with loss of initial <i>H-</i>.","possibly a habitational name from Arrington, a place in Cambridgeshire, named from an Old English byname, <i>Earn(a)</i>, meaning ‘eagle’ + <i>-inga-</i> ‘people or followers of’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":24,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":33,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","